WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.000
Let's do coverage. We were just talking about 100% test coverage.

00:03.000 --> 00:05.000
I'm going to show you how to measure that with vitest now.

00:05.000 --> 00:07.000
We are going to install one more thing.

00:07.000 --> 00:23.000
npm install capital D at vitest slash coverage dash v8 2.1.3.

00:23.000 --> 00:26.000
Okay.

00:26.000 --> 00:29.000
I showed you how to do this with, I'm going to show you how to do with v8.

00:29.000 --> 00:35.000
I think it's the better library, but if you are bent on using Istanbul,

00:35.000 --> 00:39.000
you can do that as well, and that will get the Istanbul one as well.

00:39.000 --> 00:42.000
If it doesn't make any difference to you, just stick with v8.

00:42.000 --> 00:46.000
Istanbul has been the gold standard for longer than my career.

00:46.000 --> 00:50.000
It's been the test coverage tool forever.

00:50.000 --> 00:54.000
But v8 is the new hotness.

00:54.000 --> 00:58.000
All right. So I want you to go to your Vite config really quick.

00:58.000 --> 01:07.000
And inside of, I think it just says coverage.

01:07.000 --> 01:09.000
So we are going to do coverage here.

01:09.000 --> 01:11.000
Is it inside of test? I can't tell.

01:11.000 --> 01:14.000
Yeah, it's inside of test. My notes didn't say that.

01:14.000 --> 01:18.000
But coverage.

01:18.000 --> 01:21.000
And then we are going to do our reporter.

01:21.000 --> 01:25.000
And I just have in here text. I think I have all of them.

01:25.000 --> 01:28.000
But you can choose just some of them.

01:28.000 --> 01:30.000
JSON and HTML.

01:30.000 --> 01:36.000
And this will generate all of the tests for your coverage tools.

01:36.000 --> 01:38.000
You probably don't need all of them.

01:38.000 --> 01:41.000
We'll look at the HTML one, but the JSON one can be like ingested into your

01:41.000 --> 01:46.000
like dashboards or something like that if you want to do that.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.000
Okay. That's really it, which is kind of cool to set this up.

01:50.000 --> 01:53.000
The only thing we got to go do now is in our package.json.

01:53.000 --> 01:59.000
Instead of our scripts, we're going to create one called coverage.

01:59.000 --> 02:02.000
So I'll just put this down at the bottom.

02:02.000 --> 02:09.000
Coverage. And all you're going to do is vitest dash dash coverage.

02:09.000 --> 02:11.000
And it will handle the rest.

02:11.000 --> 02:15.000
If you've never had to set up coverage by hand in like, I don't know,

02:15.000 --> 02:19.000
like eight years ago, I just want you to know that this used to suck.

02:19.000 --> 02:21.000
A lot.

02:21.000 --> 02:24.000
To instrument everything correctly to run test coverage.

02:24.000 --> 02:32.000
And the fact that vitest just does it for you is just, it's just great.

02:32.000 --> 02:36.000
npm run test colon, or no, I just called it coverage.

02:36.000 --> 02:39.000
npm run coverage, like that.

02:39.000 --> 02:41.000
It's going to run our entire testing suite.

02:41.000 --> 02:46.000
And then we get this really cool report here in our command line of what

02:46.000 --> 02:50.000
files are covered, what files aren't covered.

02:50.000 --> 02:57.000
And this is cool that we get this directly into our code base or our CLI.

02:57.000 --> 02:59.000
But we can actually do something that's even cooler.

02:59.000 --> 03:03.000
I'm going to go to my browser and I'm going to do command open.

03:03.000 --> 03:07.000
And I'm going to be in Padre Gino's here.

03:07.000 --> 03:10.000
You get this coverage directory.

03:10.000 --> 03:15.000
And just open this index.html inside of the coverage directory.

03:15.000 --> 03:20.000
Now we get like a full-on web page that describes all the test coverage.

03:20.000 --> 03:22.000
When I say coverage, I'm just saying like what files are tested and what

03:22.000 --> 03:26.000
files are not and what lines are tested and what lines are not.

03:26.000 --> 03:28.000
So let's look at our source directory.

03:28.000 --> 03:33.000
We can see that pizza.jsx, every line was covered.

03:33.000 --> 03:35.000
You can see some of them got run twice.

03:35.000 --> 03:37.000
Some of them got run once.

03:37.000 --> 03:38.000
Cool.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.000
Let's go look at cart.

03:40.000 --> 03:45.000
You can see that all of these lines were run once.

03:45.000 --> 03:48.000
But you can see it actually never got here.

03:48.000 --> 03:50.000
Why is that?

03:50.000 --> 03:51.000
Well, we gave it an empty cart.

03:51.000 --> 03:53.000
We never gave it a full cart.

03:53.000 --> 03:55.000
So this for loop never gets run.

03:55.000 --> 04:01.000
This cart.map never gets run because it never had anything in the cart.

04:01.000 --> 04:03.000
Or use pizza of the day.

04:03.000 --> 04:05.000
Some of these got run twice.

04:05.000 --> 04:06.000
This got run four times.

04:06.000 --> 04:08.000
That's kind of cool.

04:09.000 --> 04:12.000
And you can see, for example, header never tested.

04:12.000 --> 04:13.000
Same with source.

04:13.000 --> 04:16.000
Like post-contact looks like this got run, but we never hit the error case.

04:16.000 --> 04:21.000
So we don't know if it actually does the correct error.

04:21.000 --> 04:27.000
So you can see here we have 16% of statements under 17%, 45% of branches,

04:27.000 --> 04:29.000
33% of functions.

04:29.000 --> 04:32.000
Obviously, this is not a well-tested code base.

04:32.000 --> 04:34.000
I'm not purporting that it is.

04:34.000 --> 04:38.000
But I'm also going to say that I don't think 100% test coverage is a worthy goal.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.000
I think it's a waste of time most of the time.

04:40.000 --> 04:42.000
You end up writing tests that you don't care about.

04:42.000 --> 04:45.000
And tests that you don't care about are worse than tests that don't exist.

04:45.000 --> 04:47.000
It's pretty cool stuff, though, right?

04:47.000 --> 04:50.000
That this all just gets generated automatically.

04:50.000 --> 04:52.000
I think it's cool.

